vectorData.altText: 1. Which spinal levels contribute to the formation of the brachial plexus? Choose all that apply.
That's right!  The roots of the brachial plexus are the ventral rami of spinal nerves C5 - T1.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.
Unwrap the specimen of the brachial plexus provided.
1.6   C5-T1 Ventral Rami form the Brachial Plexus
spinal nerves emerging from the intervertebral foramina. These are the roots of the brachial plexus.
IDENTIFY the ventral rami of the C5 through T1
The C5 and C6 ventral rami join to form the superior trunk.
Nerves arising from the roots will contain fibres only from the one spinal level.

The C7 ventral ramus continues independently as the middle trunk.
The C8 and T1 ventral rami join to form the inferior trunk.

It should make sense to you that:
damage to the superior trunk will affect targets of both the C5 and C6 spinal nerves / levels.
damage to the inferior trunk will affect targets of both the C8 and T1 spinal nerves / levels.
